<TITLE> Govt seeks $500m recession aid from ADB </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, July 23 (bdnews24.com)Bangladesh has asked for $500m in 'emergency aid' from an Asian Development Bank fund for developing countries hit by the world recession, finance minister AMA Muhith said Thursday after a meeting with visiting ADB president Haruhiko Kuroda. ADB has raised a fund of $3 billion to assist Asia's developing nations to overcome the effects of the global economic recession. "We have requested $500 million from the fund on an emergency basis," said Muhith. The finance minister said ADB contributes $600m to the national budget every year. Kuroda, who arrived in Dhaka earlier in the day on a two-day visit, pledged to increase the annual contribution by $200m. The ADB chief said his bank had good relations with Bangladesh and hoped to continue its support to the country. bdn
